<LegalLayout
  title="Security & Compliance"
  description="DataBreef's security architecture: AES-256 encryption, read-only enforcement, live audit logs, and SOC 2-aligned practices."
  lastUpdated="April 2026"
>
  <p>
    Security is foundational to DataBreef — not an afterthought. Every architectural decision starts
    from the principle that your database is your most valuable asset, and we are only ever guests.
    This page documents how we protect that trust.
  </p>

  <h2>Read-Only by Design</h2>
  <p>
    DataBreef enforces read-only access at the database adapter layer, not just at the application level.
    Every connection opens a transaction with <code>SET TRANSACTION READ ONLY</code> before any query
    executes. This is displayed live in the audit log so you can verify it yourself.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>No <code>INSERT</code>, <code>UPDATE</code>, <code>DELETE</code>, or <code>DDL</code> is ever issued</li>
    <li>Read-only enforcement is open source and auditable on GitHub</li>
    <li>Transactions are rolled back after introspection completes</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Encryption</h2>
  <h3>Connection Strings at Rest</h3>
  <p>
    Database connection strings are encrypted with AES-256-GCM before being written to our database.
    The encryption key is never stored alongside the ciphertext. Decryption occurs in-memory, only
    during the introspection window, and the plaintext is never logged or persisted.
  </p>
  <h3>Data in Transit</h3>
  <p>
    All communication between your browser, our API, and your database is encrypted via TLS 1.2+.
    We enforce HSTS and reject connections from clients that do not support modern cipher suites.
  </p>

  <h2>Authentication & Access Control</h2>
  <p>
    DataBreef uses Auth.js v5 for authentication, supporting OAuth 2.0 (GitHub, Google) and
    email/password with secure session management. Sessions are short-lived, signed with rotating
    secrets, and invalidated on logout.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Role-based access control (RBAC) per workspace</li>
    <li>Reef (connection) access scoped to the creating user or shared team</li>
    <li>Admin actions require re-authentication</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Audit Logging</h2>
  <p>
    Every database introspection session generates a live audit log visible to the user. The log
    includes the exact SQL statements executed, timestamps, the read-only enforcement commands,
    and the result counts — so you always know exactly what DataBreef did in your database.
  </p>

  <h2>Infrastructure Security</h2>
  <p>
    DataBreef's cloud platform is deployed on Vercel and Neon, both of which maintain SOC 2 Type II
    certification. Our infrastructure follows a least-privilege model: no service has more access
    than required for its function.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Automated dependency scanning via Dependabot</li>
    <li>Secrets managed via environment variable isolation (never in source)</li>
    <li>Zero-downtime deployments with automatic rollback on failure</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Self-Hosting</h2>
  <p>
    DataBreef is open source and fully self-hostable via Docker. Self-hosted deployments keep all
    data — including connection strings and Dib outputs — entirely within your own infrastructure.
    We publish signed container images and a hardening guide in our documentation.
  </p>

  <h2>Vulnerability Disclosure</h2>
  <p>
    We operate a responsible disclosure program. If you discover a security vulnerability in
    DataBreef, please report it privately before public disclosure. We commit to acknowledging
    reports within 48 hours and providing a resolution timeline within 7 days.
  </p>

  <h2>Compliance</h2>
  <p>
    DataBreef is designed with GDPR, CCPA, and SOC 2 alignment in mind. We maintain a Data
    Processing Agreement (DPA) for enterprise customers and can provide security questionnaire
    responses upon request.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/dpa">Data Processing Agreement (DPA)</a></li>
    <li><a href="/privacy">Privacy Policy</a></li>
    <li><a href="/cookies">Cookie Policy</a></li>
  </ul>

